citations.subtitle: MASTER CYLINDER 1.9.5.4 DON’TS 1. Don’t use the fluid bled from the system for refilling or top-up the reservoir. 2. Don’t allow the brake fluid level in reservoir to fall below minimum level at any time. 3. Don’t use the fluid stored in open containers. 1.9.5.5 SERVICE RECOMMENDATION 1. Drain, flush and refill the brake fluid for every 30,000 km. 1.9.6 BRAKE FLUID HANDLING 1. Brake fluid should not be exposed to atmosphere. 2. Brake fluids are hygroscopic in nature. 3. It will absorb moisture from the atmosphere and lead to lowering of boiling point . 4. This will lead to corrosion of the internal parts of hydraulic cylinders. 5. Lowering of boiling point could lead to vaporization of the fluid under heavy braking and results in brake failure. 6. Brake fluid is subjected to repeated heating and cooling cycles which can lead to gradual deterioration of its properties. 7. Hence it is absolutely essential that the brake fluid has to be drained and replaced as recommended. 8. Remember to flush the system only with fresh brake fluid. 9. Use clean bleeder bottle while bleeding. 10. While overhauling master cylinder and wheel cylinder, use only brake fluid. 11. Never use mineral oils like petrol, kerosene, diesel etc. 12. Use only recommended brake fluid to DOT 3 specification. 13. Always buy fluid in sealed tins for filling/ topping up. 14. Never use bled brake fluid. 15. Always keep the brake fluid container lid closed to avoid moisture absorption. 16. Seal swelling is due to the usage of mineral oils for cleaning or using spurious fluid for filling/topping up or brake fluid contamination. 17. If brake fluid is contaminated drain the entire brake fluid replace all rubber components and bleed with fresh brake fluid. 18. Always keep the reservoir cap in closed condition 19. If the brake fluid is spilled on the paint work the area must be immediately washed with water. 1.9.7 INSTALLATION Note Apply brake fluid or rubber grease to sliding contact surface, when assembling

responses.query_text: "Difference between engine oil and brake fluid in tabular format"
response_messages:
**Response from Ashok Leyland's Official Documents**

## Engine Oil vs. Brake Fluid

| Feature          | Engine Oil                               | Brake Fluid                                   |
|-----------------|-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|
| **Purpose**      | Lubricates engine parts, reduces friction | Transmits braking force, prevents corrosion   |
| **Type**         | Various types (e.g., synthetic, mineral) | DOT 3 or DOT 4 (not interchangeable)       |
| **Storage**      | Sealed containers                         | Sealed containers                             |
| **Reuse**        | Generally not recommended after use      | Never reuse drained brake fluid                |
| **Contamination**| Can lead to engine damage               | Can lead to brake failure                     |
| **Moisture**     | Can degrade over time                     | Hygroscopic (absorbs moisture), lowers boiling point |
| **Other Fluids** | Do not mix with other fluids             | Do not mix with mineral oils (petrol, kerosene, diesel) |


**Additional Notes:**

*   Always use engine oil that meets the specified requirements (see document).
*   Brake fluid should not be exposed to the atmosphere.  Lowering of boiling point could lead to vaporization of the fluid under heavy braking and results in brake failure.
*   If brake fluid is contaminated, drain the entire brake fluid, replace all rubber components, and bleed with fresh brake fluid.
*   Before refilling brake fluid, drain and flush the container if changing between DOT 3 and DOT 4.
*   Always keep the brake fluid container lid closed to avoid moisture absorption.
*   If brake fluid is spilled on paintwork, wash the area immediately with water.

**Below Response is from Outside Trusted Sources. Please consult with Ashok Leyland for the most accurate and up-to-date information.**

| Feature | Engine Oil | Brake Fluid |
|---|---|---|
| **Purpose** | Lubricates engine components to reduce friction and wear. | Transmits force from the brake pedal to the brakes to stop the vehicle. |
| **Location** | Engine | Brake system |
| **Main Properties** | High viscosity, thermal stability, and detergency. | Hydraulic fluid with a high boiling point and low compressibility. |
| **Change Interval** | Typically every few months or after a certain mileage. | Typically every few years. |
| **Contamination Effects** | Can cause engine damage and reduced performance. | Can cause brake failure and reduced braking efficiency. |
| **Handling Precautions** | Avoid skin contact and dispose of properly. | Avoid contamination with dirt, water, or other fluids. |

## Questions You May Have
What are the different grades of engine oil available?
What are the symptoms of low brake fluid?
